output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/rounds/round_1/prompt.md:1:You are auditing the smart contracts in /Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/cases/anyswap/src/onchain_auto.
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:3:    "id": "F-005",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:36:    "claim": "All `Underlying` bridge and trade entrypoints transfer a nominal `amount` of the underlying into the anyToken contract and then immediately call `depositVault(amount, ...)` and burn/bridge the same nominal amount, without measuring how many units actually arrived. Fee-on-transfer, rebasing, or otherwise non-standard underlyings can therefore leave the vault underfunded while the router still bridges the full amount.",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:39:      "`anySwapOutUnderlying` transfers `amount`, then calls `depositVault(amount)` and `_anySwapOut(..., amount, ...)`",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:74:    "claim": "The router calls external token methods that explicitly return status values or actual processed amounts (`mint`, `burn`, `depositVault`, `withdrawVault`) but never validates those return values. If a supported token reports failure or partial processing without reverting, the router still emits canonical bridge/trade events and continues execution as though the accounting step succeeded.",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:75:    "impact": "A failed or short `burn`/`depositVault` on the source side can still emit `LogAnySwapOut` or trade events, enabling destination-side minting or swap settlement without full collateral being locked. Likewise, failed or partial `mint`/`withdrawVault` on the destination side can leave bridge state inconsistent, create silent insolvency, or strand users with incorrect assets.",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:79:      "All `Underlying` bridge-out functions ignore the `depositVault` return value",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:80:      "`anySwapInUnderlying`, `anySwapInAuto`, and `anySwapFeeTo` ignore `withdrawVault` return values",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:81:      "Trade entrypoints ignore `burn`/`depositVault` results before emitting bridge-trade events"
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:101:    "claim": "The router accepts arbitrary `token` and `path[0]` addresses and never verifies that they belong to an approved bridge asset set. Any contract that exposes the loose `AnyswapV1ERC20` shape can therefore be used to drive `anySwapOut*` and trade-out events that look indistinguishable from legitimate bridge activity at the router level.",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:102:    "impact": "If the off-chain relayer/MPC pipeline keys off router events without an independent token allowlist, an attacker can use a fake anyToken whose `burn`/`depositVault` semantics are non-binding to trigger destination-side minting or swaps backed by no real collateral. That can drain destination vaults or AMM liquidity.",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/findings_acc.json:105:      "Call `anySwapOutUnderlying` with a fake token whose `underlying`/`depositVault` logic is non-binding",
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/final_report.md:7:### F-005: Underlying bridge-out flows use the requested amount instead of the amount actually received
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/final_report.md:11:All `Underlying` bridge and trade entrypoints transfer a nominal `amount` of the underlying into the anyToken contract and then immediately call `depositVault(amount, ...)` and burn/bridge the same nominal amount, without measuring how many units actually arrived. Fee-on-transfer, rebasing, or otherwise non-standard underlyings can therefore leave the vault underfunded while the router still bridges the full amount.
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/final_report.md:17:- `anySwapOutUnderlying` transfers `amount`, then calls `depositVault(amount)` and `_anySwapOut(..., amount, ...)`
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/final_report.md:33:The router calls external token methods that explicitly return status values or actual processed amounts (`mint`, `burn`, `depositVault`, `withdrawVault`) but never validates those return values. If a supported token reports failure or partial processing without reverting, the router still emits canonical bridge/trade events and continues execution as though the accounting step succeeded.
output/anyswap_dualmodel_1round_p4/final_report.md:35:**Impact:** A failed or short `burn`/`depositVault` on the source side can still emit `LogAnySwapOut` or trade events, enabling destination-side minting or swap settlement without full collateral being locked. Likewise, failed or partial `mint`/`withdrawVault` on the destination side can leave bridge state inconsistent, create silent insolvency, or strand users with incorrect assets.
